Your first container.

The docker version of hello world is a single command, docker run hello world. Run it, and you get a short burst of output. That output is dense, so let us read it as a sequence, because every container you ever start follows this same path.

First, the daemon looks in your local image cache for an image called hello-world with the tag latest. On a fresh machine it is not there. So next, the daemon reaches out to docker hub, the default registry, and downloads it. Official images like this one live in a namespace called library. The image now sits in your local cache, so the next time you run the same command that download step is skipped entirely. Finally, the daemon creates a container from the image, starts it, the container prints its greeting, and then it exits.

So docker run hello-world is really shorthand for four steps. Pull the image if it is missing, create a container, start it, stream its output, and let it exit. Every docker run you ever type is some variation on those four steps.

Now, the container exited, but it is not gone. Docker keeps stopped containers around so you can inspect or restart them. Two commands prove it. Docker p-s lists running containers, and right after hello-world exits this shows nothing. Docker p-s with the all flag lists every container including stopped ones, and there you will find your hello-world container with a status of exited. Meanwhile docker images lists your local images, and hello-world is now in that list. We will learn to tidy all of this away at the end of the notebook.
